{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:39:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:39:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1827"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1827"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.09,0.01,0.83]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91645"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1827"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75215"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"457"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31290"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91645"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents with a two-week history of increasing right upper quadrant pain which is now associated with intermittent fever and sweats. He feels generally unwell and has lost 10kg weight. Three months ago he had a short holiday in Bali and one month ago had an episode of crampy abdominal pain which became worse on the right lower side. The pain was constant at this site and he noticed tenderness in this area. After a few days he felt better and did not seek any help.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is now tender the right upper quadrant. A CT scan shows three hypodense areas in the right lobe of the liver (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most likely precipitated the current illness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute pancreatitis","Acute appendicitis","Acute cholecystitis","Acute diverticulitis","Amoebiasis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhat can be surmised from the clinical picture is that the patient has a liver abscess. The aetiology of a liver abscesses can be:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epyogenic\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eamoebic\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efungal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOverall, most liver abscesses have a pyogenic origin and of these, the biliary tract will be the prime source of infection. Other conditions such diverticulitis and appendicitis can be complicated by haematogenous spread to the liver and abscess formation. Entamoeba histolytica (\u003Cstrong\u003Eamoebiasis\u003C/strong\u003E) is found globally and is transmitted by faeco-oral contact. Most infections usually remain symptom-free. Whilst it is possible that there was an intra-abdominal septic focus (eg appendicitis) to explain the liver abscess, in terms of frequency, it is most likely that the underlying cause of this patient\u0027s liver abscess was Entamoeba histolytica.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In a patient with a liver abscess, the precipitating cause must always be sought."],"references":["McNeil T, Daniel S, Gordon DL. Management of pyogenic liver abscess: a South Australian experience. ANZJ Surg doi: 10.1111/ans.15963"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75215"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1827"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21777"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21777"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2oE72O2SDElV9KIPj9uTPItEw0kNQL.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2oE72O2SDElV9KIPj9uTPItEw0kNQL.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":564,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75215"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T07:53:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T07:53:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1827"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91645"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7